subSection.paragraph:
While the diversity and phylogeny of terpene synthases in Angiosperms and Gymnosperms has been extensively reviewed (
Cao et al., 2010
; 
Chen et al., 2011
; 
Degenhardt et al., 2009
), including for diterpenes, there is comparatively little on CYPs. In one recent review, the oxidations by CYPs were presented as branching points in plant terpenoid biosynthesis (
Banerjee and Hamberger, 2017
). In this review we wish to focus on CYPs involved in plant diterpene biosynthesis with the aim to answer the following questions: 1) is there a relationship between the structural classes of diterpenes found across plant species and the CYPs that can oxidize them? 2) Are there trends in the phylogenetic distribution of CYPs that oxidize diterpenes?

One important superfamily of decorating enzymes are cytochrome P450 monooxygenases (CYPs). These enzymes typically contain a heme and can be found in organisms of all taxa (
Werck-Reichhart and Feyereisen, 2000
). In plants, they constitute the third largest multigene family and are considered as one of the main contributors to the chemical diversity of metabolites, not only because they are often promiscuous (
Guo et al., 2016
; 
Nelson and Werck-Reichhart, 2011
). The reactions catalyzed by CYPs include oxidation, dehydration, dealkylation, C-C cleavage, desaturation, decarboxylation, dimerization, isomerization, reduction and ring extension reactions. Plant CYPs transfer two electrons from the co-factors NAD(P)H and atmospheric oxygen to their substrates. In most cases in plants a cytochrome P450 reductase (CPR) is required to support the electron transfer (
Nelson and Werck-Reichhart, 2011
; 
Werck-Reichhart and Feyereisen, 2000
).

Here, we have collected all CYPs that have been characterized from plant diterpene biosynthesis to date ( Table S1 ), and have subjected them to phylogenetic analysis using the maximum likelihood method ( Fig. 2 , Table S1 ). Our phylogenetic analysis includes CYPs of 20 sub-families from the CYP 71, CYP 72 and CYP 85 clans, which carry out the oxidation of diverse plant diterpene skeletons based on published literature. In total, this comprises 61 characterized CYPs, which catalyze the formation of 98 identified products ( Table 1 ). In most cases these are macrocyclic or labdane-related diterpenoids. Diterpene metabolism in plants is dominated by a few CYP clans, with the CYP 71 and CYP 85 clans being major contributors and fewer representatives from the CYP 72 clan. This is not especially surprising because the CYP 71 and CYP 85 clans combined comprise the majority of the CYP families in plants ( Nelson and Werck-Reichhart, 2011 ). Interestingly however, only few families within these clans are represented among the diterpene oxidizing CYPs ( Fig. 2 ). In the CYP 85 clan, only three families are represented: CYP 725 A involved in taxane biosynthesis from yew trees (
Taxus sp.
), CYP 720B from conifer diterpene resin acid (DRA) biosynthesis and CYP 88 A , which encodes the kaurenoic acid oxidase (KAO). CYP 725 A and CYP 720B are families specific to Gymnosperms, whereas KAO can be found in all plant families except Bryophytes ( Miyazaki et al., 2011 ). However, all three CYP families from the CYP 85 clan appear to be ancient CYPs, which most likely evolved early in the evolution of Gymnosperms and Angiosperms.

Little is known about the 
CYP
72 clan with only a few characterized members to date. They are involved in steviol biosynthesis and gibberellin catabolism pointing to the close relationship of specialized diterpene pathways and hormone metabolism (
Brandle and Telmer, 2007
; 
Magome et al., 2013
; 
Nomura et al., 2013
; 
Zhang et al., 2011
; 
Zhu et al., 2006
). 
CYP
714 is the only family of this clan represented in the plant diterpene CYPs (
Fig. 2
).

Phytoalexins represent a group of plant anti-microbial compounds which are produced upon biotic or abiotic stress. They originate from different metabolite classes and are found in many plant species (
Dao et al., 2011
; 
Jeandet, 2015
). Labdane-related phytoalexins and oryzalide-related compounds have been found so far only in 

Zea mays

containing kauralexins, and in rice, which produces oryzalexin S, momilactone 
A
and B, oryzalides A-C, phytocassanes A-E, oryzalexins A-F, oryzalic acids and oryzadiones (
Grayer and Kokubun, 2001
; 
Schmelz et al., 2011
, 
2014
). Rice phytoalexins are of potential medicinal interest due to their antibiotic activity (
Peters, 2006
). 
In vivo
they inhibit seed germination of surrounding plants and exhibit anti-fungal activity upon 

Magnaporthe grisea

infection (
Kato-Noguchi et al., 2002
; 
Kato-Noguchi and Peters, 2013
; 
Kodama et al., 1992
; 
Toyomasu et al., 2014
; 
Xu et al., 2012
).

subSubSection.paragraph:
In tomato (

Solanum lycopersicum
)

, the diterpene lycosantalene is synthesized not from the usual precursor GGPP, but from nerylneryl diphosphate, which is a C20 
cis
-prenyl diphosphate (
Zi et al., 2014b
). SlCYP71BN1 oxidizes lycosantalene twice to produce epoxy-lycosantalene and lycosantanolol (
Matsuba et al., 2015
; 
Zi et al., 2014b
). The involved genes are located in a metabolic gene cluster on chromosome 8 including an alcohol oxidase, five TPS (including TPS21), 
cis
-prenyl transferases, alcohol acyltransferases and an addition non-functional CYP (
Matsuba et al., 2015
).

subSection.paragraph:
Plant diterpenoids are one of the most important metabolic group contributing to plant fitness and displaying an enormous potential for pharmaceutical and industrial applications (
Kemper et al., 2017
; 
Wang et al., 2005
; 
Zerbe and Bohlmann, 2015a
). The underlying chemical diversity is established first by diterpene synthases and is typically followed by oxidations and rearrangements, which are carried out essentially by CYPs that exhibit varying degrees of substrate promiscuity. To date, we understand some diterpene biosyntheses whose genes are sometimes organized in metabolic clusters. However, our knowledge is still limited because the elucidated pathways of some macrocyclic and labdane-related compounds represent only a small fraction of the diterpene metabolome in plants. For example, the biosynthesis of triptolide, tanshinones, clerodane and other diterpenoids still remains poorly understood. In some of the mentioned pathways the participating diTPS have been characterized, but the identification of downstream decorating enzymes still remains to be done (
Andersen-Ranberg et al., 2016
; 
Hansen et al., 2017
; 
Su et al., 2017
).
